<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
    Android has forbidden cleartext HTTP since API 28, and it is right to.

    But this app's fallback address is the PC on your own wifi — http://192.168.x.x:7777 —
    and `kaip serve --wifi` drops the tunnel entirely, so plain HTTP over the local network
    IS the feature. Without this, the app simply could not reach a PC on the LAN: "--wifi"
    was a mode that could not possibly work, and the failure came back as an Android policy
    error that says nothing about what you did wrong.

    It has to be allowed in general rather than for one address: the config is compiled into
    the APK, and the IP of your PC is not known until you scan the QR. Android's
    <domain> takes hostnames and literal IPs — not CIDR ranges — so there is no way to say
    "private networks only" here.

    What limits the surface is not this file: it is that the app only ever talks to ONE
    address, the one inside the pairing QR, which you scanned off your own screen. And the
    tunnel is https and stays https — everything that crosses the internet is encrypted
    twice over (TLS, and the AES-256-GCM seal underneath it that Cloudflare cannot open).
-->
<network-security-config>
    <base-config cleartextTrafficPermitted="true" />
</network-security-config>
